Kiarostami]], Iranian director (died 2016)\n*June 23 \u2013 [[Adam Faith]], English actor and singer (died 2003)\n*July 4 \u2013 [[Karolyn Grimes]], American actress\n*July 7 \u2013 [[Ringo Starr]], English drummer ([[The Beatles]])\n*July 13 \u2013 [[Patrick Stewart]], English actor\n*July 18 \u2013 [[James Brolin]], American actor\n*July 24 \u2013 [[Dan Hedaya]], American actor\n*August 3 \u2013 [[Martin Sheen]], American actor\n*August 15 \n** [[Maria Grazia Buccella]], Italian actress\n** [[Ze'ev Revach]], Israeli comedian, film actor, director\n*August 19 \u2013 [[Jill St. John]], American actress\n*August 27 \u2013 [[Sonny Sharrock]], American jazz guitarist (died 1994)\n*August 31 \u2013 [[Jack Thompson (actor)|Jack Thompson]], Australian actor\n*September 5 \u2013 [[Raquel Welch]], American actress\n*September 11 \u2013 [[Brian De Palma]], American director, producer and screenwriter\n*September 22 \u2013 [[Anna Karina]], Danish-born French actress, director and singer (died 2019)\n*October 9 \u2013 [[John Lennon]], English singer-songwriter and musician ([[The Beatles]]) (shot to death 1980)\n*October 14 \u2013 [[Cliff Richard]], English singer and actor\n*October 19 \u2013 [[Michael Gambon]], Irish-born British actor\n*November 5 \u2013 [[Elke Sommer]], German actress\n*November 13 \u2013 [[Rudolf Schwarzkogler]], Austrian experimental filmmaker (died 1969)\n*November 15 \u2013 [[Sam Waterston]], American actor\n*November 20 \u2013 [[Helma Sanders-Brahms]], German director (died 2014)\n*November 27 \u2013 [[Bruce Lee]], Chinese-American martial artist and actor (died 1973)\n*December 1 \u2013 [[Richard Pryor]], American comedian and actor (died 2005)\n*December 13 \u2013 [[Volli K\u00e4ro]], Estonian actor\n\n==Deaths==\n* January 4 \u2013 [[Flora Finch]], 72, American actress, ''[[A Cure for Pokeritis]]'', ''[[The Cat and the Canary (1927 film)|The Cat and the Canary]]'', ''[[Quality Street (1927 film)|Quality Street]]'', ''[[Her Crowning Glory]]''\n* February 20 \u2013 [[George Periolat]], 66, American actor, ''[[The Mark of Zorro (1920 film)|The Mark of Zorro]]'', ''[[One Rainy Afternoon]]'', ''[[Morning Glory (1933 film)|Morning Glory]]'', ''[[What Price Hollywood?]]''\n* March 5 \u2013 [[Maxine Elliott]], 66, American actress, ''[[Fighting Odds]]''\n* April 9 \u2013 [[Mrs. Patrick Campbell]], 75, English actress, ''[[Riptide (film)|Riptide]]'', ''[[One More River]]''\n* April 11 \u2013 [[Hemmo Kallio]], 77, Finnish actor, ''[[Anna Liisa]]'' \n* May 25 \u2013 [[Joe De Grasse]], 67, Canadian-born American film director, ''[[Heart o' the Hills]]'', ''[[The Scarlet Car]]'', ''[[The Girl of the Night]]''\n* July 1 \u2013 [[Ben Turpin]], 70, American actor, ''[[Saps at Sea]]'', ''[[Mr. Flip]]'', ''[[A Clever Dummy]]''\n* July 15 \u2013 [[Donald Calthrop]], 52, English actor, ''[[Scrooge (1935 film)|Scrooge]]'', ''[[Blackmail (1929 film)|Blackmail]]'', ''[[Murder!]]'', ''[[Major Barbara (film)|Major Barbara]]''\n* September 25 \u2013 [[Marguerite Clark]], 57, American actress, ''[[Scrambled Wives]]'', ''[[Easy to Get]]'', ''[[All of a Sudden Peggy]]'', ''[[A Girl Named Mary]]''\n* October 10 \u2013 [[Berton Churchill]], 63, Canadian actor, ''[[Stagecoach (1939 film)|Stagecoach]]'', ''[[I Am a Fugitive from a Chain Gang]]'', ''[[In Old Chicago]]'', ''[[Heroes for Sale (film)|Heroes for Sale]]''\n* October 12 \u2013 [[Tom Mix]], 60, American actor, ''[[The Miracle Rider]]'', ''[[Riders of the Purple Sage (1925 film)|Riders of the Purple Sage]]'', ''[[Sky High (1922 film)|Sky High]]''\n* December 13 \u2013 [[Wilfred Lucas]], 69, Canadian-born American actor, screenwriter, director, ''[[Modern Times (film)|Modern Times]]'', ''[[A Chump at Oxford]]'', ''[[The Girl and Her Trust]]''\n\n==Debuts==\n*[[Jack Albertson]] \u2013 ''[[Strike up the Band (film)|Strike up the Band]]''\n*[[Dana Andrews]] \u2013 ''[[Lucky Cisco Kid]]''\n*[[Anne Baxter]] \u2013 ''[[20 Mule Team]]''\n*[[Hugh Griffith]] \u2013 ''[[Night Train to Munich]]''\n*[[Van Johnson]] \u2013 ''[[Too Many Girls (film)|Too Many Girls]]''\n*[[Arthur Kennedy]] \u2013 ''[[City for Conquest]]''\n*[[Karl Malden]] \u2013 ''[[They Knew What They Wanted (film)|They Knew What They Wanted]]''\n*[[Terry Moore (actress)|Terry Moore]] \u2013 ''[[Maryland (1940 film)|Maryland]]''\n*[[Robert Ryan]] \u2013 ''[[The Ghost Breakers]]''\n*[[Gene Tierney]] \u2013 ''[[The Return of Frank James]]''\n*[[David Tomlinson]] \u2013 ''[[Garrison Follies]]''\n*[[Forrest Tucker]] \u2013 ''[[The Westerner (1940 film)|The Westerner]]''\n*[[Gig Young]] \u2013 ''[[Misbehaving Husbands]]''\n*[[Deborah Kerr]] \u2013 ''[[Contraband (1940 film)|Contraband]]''\n*[[Donna Reed]] \u2013 ''[[Convicted Woman]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{1940 films}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1940 In Film}}\n[[Category:1940 in film| ]]\n[[Category:Film by year]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Flowing Gold", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1940_in_film"}
{"title_page": "Edward Pawley", "text_new": "{{More citations needed |date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image       = <!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Bigtownpawley.jpg|right|thumb|350px|In this posed NBC publicity photo, Edward Pawley is seen in the role of Steve Wilson from radio's ''[[Big Town]]''.]] -->\n| birth_name  = Edward Joel Pawley\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1901|3|16}}\n| birth_place = [[Kansas City, Missouri]], U.S.\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1988|1|27|1901|3|16}}\n| death_place = [[Charlottesville, Virginia]], U.S.\n| yearsactive = 1919&ndash;1951\n| spouse      = Martina May Martin (1922&ndash;1929) (divorced) 1 child<br>[[Helen Shipman]] (1937&ndash;1984) (her death)\n| children    = 1\n}}\n\n'''Edward Joel Pawley''' (March 16, 1901 in [[Kansas City, Missouri]] &ndash; January 27, 1988 in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]])<ref name=\"ibdb\" /> was an American actor of radio, films and Broadway. The full name on his birth certificate is Edward Joel Stone Pawley; he never used the Stone name, which derived from a Stone family in Illinois.\n\n== Early years ==\nAt maturity, Pawley was 5'10\" tall with thick black hair and blue eyes. While in high school, he became interested in both journalism and acting. Acting won out after taking drama classes and appearing in high school plays. He moved to New York City in 1920 to pursue a career in the theater.\n\n==Broadway==\nPawley began his [[theatre|theatrical]] career in 1920 and reached the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] stage in 1923 in ''[[The Shame Woman]]''. He went on to star in various well-known Broadway plays, including ''[[Elmer Gantry (play)|Elmer Gantry]]'' (1928), ''[[Processional (film)|Processional]]'' (1928), ''[[Subway Express]]'' (1929), ''[[Two Seconds]]'' (1931), ''[[Life Begins (film)|Life Begins]]'' (1932) and ''[[The Willow and I]]'' (1942).<ref name=\"ibdb\">{{cite web |title=Edward Pawley |url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/edward-pawley-55757 |website=Internet Broadway Database |publisher=The Broadway League |accessdate=October 22, 2019}}</ref> Pawley's rich, baritone voice was hailed by leading journalists of the day, including [[Walter Winchell]] and [[Heywood Hale Broun]]. Although he was probably best known in the theater for his portrayal of [[Elmer Gantry]] in the Broadway play of the same name, it was his portrayal of John Allen in ''[[Two Seconds]]'' that brought him to the attention of Hollywood by way of [[Warner Brothers]]. Winchell wrote that Pawley received a standing ovation after his opening night performance in the 1931 play ''[[Two Seconds]]''.\n\n==Hollywood==\nNot long after [[sound film]] came into vogue, Pawley left the theater in 1932 and went to [[Hollywood]] where he performed in over 50 movies during a relatively brief (for Hollywood) ten-year span. He had feature roles in such movies as ''The Hoosier Schoolboy''<ref>{{cite news |title=Strand: Stage His Love |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40148601/edward_pawley/ |accessdate=December 5, 2019 |work=Kingsport Times |date=February 26, 1939 |location=Tennessee, Kingsport |page=18|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> with [[Mickey Rooney]], ''[[G Men]]'' with [[James Cagney]], ''[[The Oklahoma Kid]]'' with Cagney and [[Humphrey Bogart]], ''[[King Solomon of Broadway]]'' with [[Edmund Lowe]] and Louise Henry, ''[[Each Dawn I Die]]'' with [[George Raft]] and Cagney, ''[[Tom Sawyer, Detective]]'' with [[Janet Waldo]] and [[Donald O'Connor]]  and ''[[Romance on the Range (film)|Romance on the Range]]'' with [[Roy Rogers]] and [[Gabby Hayes]]. He played mostly \"bad guy\" roles in [[gangster]], [[Horror film|horror]], [[comedy]] and [[Western films]]. He became friends with Cagney (with whom he made five movies), [[Jackie Cooper]] (four movies) and [[Francis Lederer]].  One of his earliest friends in the entertainment industry was [[Arthur Hughes (actor)|Arthur Hughes]], who played Bill Davidson on the long-running radio show ''[[Just Plain Bill]]''. Hughes also acted in some Broadway plays and was Pawley's best man at his wedding in 1922 to stage actress Martina May Martin.\n\n==Radio==\nPawley became disenchanted with Hollywood during the attempted infiltration by the [[communists]] in the late 1930s and early 1940s and left in 1942. He returned briefly to Broadway, where he starred with Gregory Peck in what was Peck's second Broadway play titled ''[[The Willow and I]]''. In the 1930s, Pawley had performed leading romantic roles on ''[[The Collier Hour]]'' radio program. He resumed work in radio after returning to New York City. He played opposite [[Lucille Wall]] in the radio soap opera ''[[Portia Faces Life]]'' as \"Love Story Boy and Girl.\"{{Citation needed |date=October 2019}} Later in 1943, Pawley played Steve Wilson on the radio drama series ''[[Big Town]]'',<ref name=\"rp\">{{cite book|last1=Terrace|first1=Vincent|title=Radio Programs, 1924-1984: A Catalog of More Than 1800 Shows|date=1999|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc.|isbn=978-0-7864-4513-4|pages=40-41}}</ref>, replacing [[Edward G. Robinson]], who had played the role from 1937\u201342 when the show was produced in Hollywood. Wilson's sidekick on ''Big Town'' was \"girl reporter\" Lorelei Kilbourne, played by [[Fran Carlon]].  Pawley had performed with Robinson in 1926 in a comedy play titled \"[[The Stolen Lady]]\" at \"[[Werba's Brooklyn Theater]]\".\n\nDuring Pawley's eight-year reign, ''Big Town'' achieved the number one rating for reporter-type radio drama shows. In the January 1948 Nielson ratings, the show was ranked #12 among all radio programs, ahead of such popular shows as ''[[Suspense (radio program)|Suspense]]'', ''[[The Adventures of Sam Spade|Sam Spade]]'', ''[[Mr. District Attorney]]'', ''[[The FBI in Peace and War]]'', ''[[Blondie (radio)|Blondie]]'' and ''[[Mr. and Mrs. North]]''.  It also was in the Top 10 of all radio shows more times than any other that year except for [[The Bob Hope Show]] and [[Fibber McGee and Molly]].  His audience was estimated anywhere from 10-20 million listeners.\n\n==Retirement==\nPawley left ''Big Town'' in 1951 and retired near the small village of [[Amissville, Virginia|Amissville]] in rural [[Rappahannock County, Virginia]]. He had fallen in love with the state while touring with the 1920 play ''[[East Is West]]'', his first professional acting role. Pawley would become the quintessential \"Virginia gentleman\" and was loved for his [[integrity]], [[patriotism]] and charm. He was admired for his vocabulary and speaking voice, as well as his status as an entertainer in three different media forms (theater, film, and radio). He raised and sold championship goats, wrote poetry and was a part-time announcer at local radio station [[WCVA (AM)|WCVA]] in [[Culpeper, Virginia]].  At WCVA, he replaced (Robert Gibson Corder, Ph.D.), who would later write Pawley's biography. Pawley beame a member of The Lambs (the actor's club) in 1951.\n\nPawley moved to [[Rock Mills, Virginia]] in the mid-1950s and lived on the original site of the Rock Mill near the confluence of the [[Thornton River|Thornton]] and [[Rush River (Virginia)|Rush]] rivers, fulfilling a dream of living close to nature. In addition to a goat farm, he and his wife maintained an [[organic vegetable farm]] and produced pesticide-free vegetables, goat milk and cheese. They ran a grocery store, the \"Cash and Totem Store\", where they sold some of their own produce and his wife sold her \"Virginia Honey Girl\" line of fruits preserved in honey.\n\nPawley and his wife were proponents of \"back-to-the-earth living with nature\" before it became popular. \n\nPawley died on January 27, 1988 of a heart condition at the [[University of Virginia Medical Center]] in Charlottesville, Virginia. He and his second wife had no children, but in his will named Jane, Ross, Kathyrn, Juia, Richard and Robin Rottier as his spiritual children. Both he and his wife, who died in 1984, were cremated and their ashes scattered at their favorite spot, \"Roaring Rock\", alongside the Rush River, which partially flows through their former estate in Rock Mills. A raised bronze plaque at that site is a memorial to their lives and careers in the entertainment medium.\n\nPawley had two younger brothers who were also actors, [[William M. \"Bud\" Pawley]] (b. ca. 1903) and [[J. Anthony Pawley]] (b. ca. 1910).  Both acted in Broadway plays and in films, though neither achieved the success and acclaim of their older brother.\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1922, Pawley married his high school sweetheart, Martina May Martin, a professional stage actress. They had one child, Martin Herbert Pawley (b. 1923). They divorced, only to remarry and divorce again. In 1937, Pawley married the then-popular Broadway singer, dancer and actress [[Helen Shipman]]. They remained married for 47 years until her death on April 13, 1984.\n\n==Partial filmography ==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[Thirteen Women]]'' (1932) - Chauffeur Burns\n* ''[[Tess of the Storm Country (1932 film)|Tess of the Storm Country]]'' (1932) - Ben Letts\n* ''[[Footlight Parade]]'' (1933, unbilled)\n* ''[[Olsen's Big Moment]]'' (1933) - Joe 'Monk' West (uncredited)\n* ''[[Murders in the Zoo]]'' (1933) - Bob Taylor (uncredited)\n* ''[[Bureau of Missing Persons]]'' (1933) - Waterfront Diner Wanting Sugar (uncredited)\n* ''[[Treasure Island (1934 film)|Treasure Island]]'' (1934) - Pirate of the Spanish Main\n* ''[[Helldorado (film)|Helldorado]]'' (1935, unbilled) - Miner (uncredited)\n* ''[[Mississippi (film)|Mississippi]]'' (1935) - Joe Patterson\n* ''[[G Men]]'' (1935) - Danny Leggett\n* ''[[Dante's Inferno (1935 film)|Dante's Inferno]]'' (1935, unbilled) - Clinton - Ship's Officer (uncredited)\n* ''[[King Solomon of Broadway]]'' (1935) - John 'Ice' Larson\n* ''[[Tough Guy (film)|Tough Guy]]'' (1936) - Tony - Gangster\n* ''[[Sworn Enemy (film)|Sworn Enemy]]'' (1936) - 'Dutch' McTurck\n* ''[[Sinner Take All]]'' (1936) - Royce\n* ''[[Dangerous Number]]'' (1937, unbilled) - Second Detective (uncredited)\n* ''[[Mountain Justice (1930 film)|Mountain Justice]]'' (1937) - Tod Miller\n* ''[[Hoosier Schoolboy]]'' (1937) - Captain Fred Carter\n* ''[[It Can't Last Forever]]'' (1937) - Cronin\n* ''[[The Last Gangster]]'' (1937) - Brockett (uncredited)\n* ''[[White Banners]]'' (1938) - Bill Ellis\n* ''[[Dangerous to Know]]'' (1938) - John Rance\n* ''[[Gun Law (1938 film)|Gun Law]]'' (1938) - The Raven\n* ''[[You and Me (1938 film)|You and Me]]'' (1938, unbilled) - Dutch (uncredited)\n* ''[[Romance of the Limberlost]]'' (1938) - Corson\n* ''[[Prison Break (1938 film)|Prison Break]]'' (1938) - Joe Fenderson\n* ''[[Little Tough Guy]]'' (1938) - Jim Boylan\n* ''[[Smashing the Rackets]]'' (1938) - Chin Martin\n* ''[[Sons of the Legion]]'' (1938) - Gunman Baker\n* ''[[Angels with Dirty Faces]]'' (1938) - Edwards\n* ''[[Tom Sawyer, Detective (film)|Tom Sawyer, Detective]]'' (1938) - Brace Dunlap\n* ''[[The Oklahoma Kid]]'' (1939) - Doolin\n* ''[[Money to Loan]]'' (1939, Short) - Calumette (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Lady's from Kentucky]]'' (1939) - Spike Cronin\n* ''[[Unmarried (film)|Unmarried]]'' (1939) - Swade\n* ''[[Help Wanted (1939 film)|Help Wanted]]'' (1939, Short) - Harry\n* ''[[Each Dawn I Die]]'' (1939) - Dale\n* ''[[The Big Guy]]'' (1939) - Buckhart\n* ''Old Hickory'' (1939, Short) - Minor Role (uncredited)\n* ''[[Castle on the Hudson]]'' (1940) - Black Jack\n* ''[[River's End (1940 film)|River's End]]'' (1940) - Frank Crandell\n* ''[[Flowing Gold (1940 film)|Flowing Gold]]'' (1940) - Collins\n* ''[[Texas Rangers Ride Again]]'' (1940) - Palo Pete\n* ''[[The San Francisco Docks|San Francisco Docks]]'' (1940) - Monte March\n* ''[[Riders of Death Valley]]'' (1941, Serial) \n* ''[[Hit the Road]]'' (1941) - Spike the Butcher\n* ''[[Hold That Ghost]]'' (1941) - High Collar (uncredited)\n* ''[[Treat 'Em Rough]]'' (1942) - Martin\n* ''[[True to the Army]]'' (1942) - Junior\n* ''[[Romance on the Range (film)|Romance on the Range]]'' (1942) - Jerome Banning\n* ''[[Flight Lieutenant (film)|Flight Lieutenant]]'' (1942) - Larsen (uncredited)\n* ''[[Eyes of the Underworld]]'' (1943) - Lance Merlin\n* ''[[The Desperadoes]]'' (1943) - Blackie (uncredited) (final film role)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0668023|name=Edward Pawley}}\n* {{IBDB name|55757}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pawley, Edward}}\n[[Category:1901 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male radio actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Kansas City, Missouri]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:People from Rappahannock County, Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed |date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image       = <!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Bigtownpawley.jpg|right|thumb|350px|In this posed NBC publicity photo, Edward Pawley is seen in the role of Steve Wilson from radio's ''[[Big Town]]''.]] -->\n| birth_name  = Edward Joel Pawley\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1901|3|16}}\n| birth_place = [[Kansas City, Missouri]], U.S.\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1988|1|27|1901|3|16}}\n| death_place = [[Charlottesville, Virginia]], U.S.\n| yearsactive = 1919&ndash;1951\n| spouse      = Martina May Martin (1922&ndash;1929) (divorced) 1 child<br>[[Helen Shipman]] (1937&ndash;1984) (her death)\n| children    = 1\n}}\n\n'''Edward Joel Pawley''' (March 16, 1901 in [[Kansas City, Missouri]] &ndash; January 27, 1988 in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]])<ref name=\"ibdb\" /> was an American actor of radio, films and Broadway. The full name on his birth certificate is Edward Joel Stone Pawley; he never used the Stone name, which derived from a Stone family in Illinois.\n\n== Early years ==\nAt maturity, Pawley was 5'10\" tall with thick black hair and blue eyes. While in high school, he became interested in both journalism and acting