d [[Humphrey Bogart]], ''[[King Solomon of Broadway]]'' with [[Edmund Lowe]] and Louise Henry, ''[[Each Dawn I Die]]'' with [[George Raft]] and Cagney, ''[[Tom Sawyer, Detective]]'' with [[Janet Waldo]] and [[Donald O'Connor]]  and ''[[Romance on the Range (film)|Romance on the Range]]'' with [[Roy Rogers]] and [[Gabby Hayes]]. He played mostly \"bad guy\" roles in [[gangster]], [[Horror film|horror]], [[comedy]] and [[Western films]]. He became friends with Cagney (with whom he made five movies), [[Jackie Cooper]] (four movies) and [[Francis Lederer]].  One of his earliest friends in the entertainment industry was [[Arthur Hughes (actor)|Arthur Hughes]], who played Bill Davidson on the long-running radio show ''[[Just Plain Bill]]''. Hughes also acted in some Broadway plays and was Pawley's best man at his wedding in 1922 to stage actress Martina May Martin.\n\n==Radio==\nPawley became disenchanted with Hollywood during the attempted infiltration by the [[communists]] in the late 1930s and early 1940s and left in 1942. He returned briefly to Broadway, where he starred with Gregory Peck in what was Peck's second Broadway play titled ''[[The Willow and I]]''. In the 1930s, Pawley had performed leading romantic roles on ''[[The Collier Hour]]'' radio program. He resumed work in radio after returning to New York City. He played opposite [[Lucille Wall]] in the radio soap opera ''[[Portia Faces Life]]'' as \"Love Story Boy and Girl.\"{{Citation needed |date=October 2019}} Later in 1943, Pawley played Steve Wilson on the radio drama series ''[[Big Town]]'',<ref name=\"rp\">{{cite book|last1=Terrace|first1=Vincent|title=Radio Programs, 1924-1984: A Catalog of More Than 1800 Shows|date=1999|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc.|isbn=978-0-7864-4513-4|pages=40-41}}</ref>, replacing [[Edward G. Robinson]], who had played the role from 1937\u201342 when the show was produced in Hollywood. Wilson's sidekick on ''Big Town'' was \"girl reporter\" Lorelei Kilbourne, played by [[Fran Carlon]].  Pawley had performed with Robinson in 1926 in a comedy play titled \"[[The Stolen Lady]]\" at \"[[Werba's Brooklyn Theater]]\".\n\nDuring Pawley's eight-year reign, ''Big Town'' achieved the number one rating for reporter-type radio drama shows. In the January 1948 Nielson ratings, the show was ranked #12 among all radio programs, ahead of such popular shows as ''[[Suspense (radio program)|Suspense]]'', ''[[The Adventures of Sam Spade|Sam Spade]]'', ''[[Mr. District Attorney]]'', ''[[The FBI in Peace and War]]'', ''[[Blondie (radio)|Blondie]]'' and ''[[Mr. and Mrs. North]]''.  It also was in the Top 10 of all radio shows more times than any other that year except for [[The Bob Hope Show]] and [[Fibber McGee and Molly]].  His audience was estimated anywhere from 10-20 million listeners.\n\n==Retirement==\nPawley left ''Big Town'' in 1951 and retired near the small village of [[Amissville, Virginia|Amissville]] in rural [[Rappahannock County, Virginia]]. He had fallen in love with the state while touring with the 1920 play ''[[East Is West]]'', his first professional acting role. Pawley would become the quintessential \"Virginia gentleman\" and was loved for his [[integrity]], [[patriotism]] and charm. He was admired for his vocabulary and speaking voice, as well as his status as an entertainer in three different media forms (theater, film, and radio). He raised and sold championship goats, wrote poetry and was a part-time announcer at local radio station [[WCVA (AM)|WCVA]] in [[Culpeper, Virginia]].  At WCVA, he replaced (Robert Gibson Corder, Ph.D.), who would later write Pawley's biography. Pawley beame a member of The Lambs (the actor's club) in 1951.\n\nPawley moved to [[Rock Mills, Virginia]] in the mid-1950s and lived on the original site of the Rock Mill near the confluence of the [[Thornton River|Thornton]] and [[Rush River (Virginia)|Rush]] rivers, fulfilling a dream of living close to nature. In addition to a goat farm, he and his wife maintained an [[organic vegetable farm]] and produced pesticide-free vegetables, goat milk and cheese. They ran a grocery store, the \"Cash and Totem Store\", where they sold some of their own produce and his wife sold her \"Virginia Honey Girl\" line of fruits preserved in honey.\n\nPawley and his wife were proponents of \"back-to-the-earth living with nature\" before it became popular. \n\nPawley died on January 27, 1988 of a heart condition at the [[University of Virginia Medical Center]] in Charlottesville, Virginia. He and his second wife had no children, but in his will named Jane, Ross, Kathyrn, Juia, Richard and Robin Rottier as his spiritual children. Both he and his wife, who died in 1984, were cremated and their ashes scattered at their favorite spot, \"Roaring Rock\", alongside the Rush River, which partially flows through their former estate in Rock Mills. A raised bronze plaque at that site is a memorial to their lives and careers in the entertainment medium.\n\nPawley had two younger brothers who were also actors, [[William M. \"Bud\" Pawley]] (b. ca. 1903) and [[J. Anthony Pawley]] (b. ca. 1910).  Both acted in Broadway plays and in films, though neither achieved the success and acclaim of their older brother.\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1922, Pawley married his high school sweetheart, Martina May Martin, a professional stage actress. They had one child, Martin Herbert Pawley (b. 1923). They divorced, only to remarry and divorce again. In 1937, Pawley married the then-popular Broadway singer, dancer and actress [[Helen Shipman]]. They remained married for 47 years until her death on April 13, 1984.\n\n==Partial filmography ==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[Thirteen Women]]'' (1932) - Chauffeur Burns\n* ''[[Tess of the Storm Country (1932 film)|Tess of the Storm Country]]'' (1932) - Ben Letts\n* ''[[Footlight Parade]]'' (1933, unbilled)\n* ''[[Olsen's Big Moment]]'' (1933) - Joe 'Monk' West (uncredited)\n* ''[[Murders in the Zoo]]'' (1933) - Bob Taylor (uncredited)\n* ''[[Bureau of Missing Persons]]'' (1933) - Waterfront Diner Wanting Sugar (uncredited)\n* ''[[Treasure Island (1934 film)|Treasure Island]]'' (1934) - Pirate of the Spanish Main\n* ''[[Helldorado (film)|Helldorado]]'' (1935, unbilled) - Miner (uncredited)\n* ''[[Mississippi (film)|Mississippi]]'' (1935) - Joe Patterson\n* ''[[G Men]]'' (1935) - Danny Leggett\n* ''[[Dante's Inferno (1935 film)|Dante's Inferno]]'' (1935, unbilled) - Clinton - Ship's Officer (uncredited)\n* ''[[King Solomon of Broadway]]'' (1935) - John 'Ice' Larson\n* ''[[Tough Guy (film)|Tough Guy]]'' (1936) - Tony - Gangster\n* ''[[Sworn Enemy (film)|Sworn Enemy]]'' (1936) - 'Dutch' McTurck\n* ''[[Sinner Take All]]'' (1936) - Royce\n* ''[[Dangerous Number]]'' (1937, unbilled) - Second Detective (uncredited)\n* ''[[Mountain Justice (1930 film)|Mountain Justice]]'' (1937) - Tod Miller\n* ''[[Hoosier Schoolboy]]'' (1937) - Captain Fred Carter\n* ''[[It Can't Last Forever]]'' (1937) - Cronin\n* ''[[The Last Gangster]]'' (1937) - Brockett (uncredited)\n* ''[[White Banners]]'' (1938) - Bill Ellis\n* ''[[Dangerous to Know]]'' (1938) - John Rance\n* ''[[Gun Law (1938 film)|Gun Law]]'' (1938) - The Raven\n* ''[[You and Me (1938 film)|You and Me]]'' (1938, unbilled) - Dutch (uncredited)\n* ''[[Romance of the Limberlost]]'' (1938) - Corson\n* ''[[Prison Break (1938 film)|Prison Break]]'' (1938) - Joe Fenderson\n* ''[[Little Tough Guy]]'' (1938) - Jim Boylan\n* ''[[Smashing the Rackets]]'' (1938) - Chin Martin\n* ''[[Sons of the Legion]]'' (1938) - Gunman Baker\n* ''[[Angels with Dirty Faces]]'' (1938) - Edwards\n* ''[[Tom Sawyer, Detective (film)|Tom Sawyer, Detective]]'' (1938) - Brace Dunlap\n* ''[[The Oklahoma Kid]]'' (1939) - Doolin\n* ''[[Money to Loan]]'' (1939, Short) - Calumette (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Lady's from Kentucky]]'' (1939) - Spike Cronin\n* ''[[Unmarried (film)|Unmarried]]'' (1939) - Swade\n* ''[[Help Wanted (1939 film)|Help Wanted]]'' (1939, Short) - Harry\n* ''[[Each Dawn I Die]]'' (1939) - Dale\n* ''[[The Big Guy]]'' (1939) - Buckhart\n* ''Old Hickory'' (1939, Short) - Minor Role (uncredited)\n* ''[[Castle on the Hudson]]'' (1940) - Black Jack\n* ''[[River's End (1940 film)|River's End]]'' (1940) - Frank Crandell\n* ''[[Flowing Gold]]'' (1940) - Collins\n* ''[[Texas Rangers Ride Again]]'' (1940) - Palo Pete\n* ''[[The San Francisco Docks|San Francisco Docks]]'' (1940) - Monte March\n* ''[[Riders of Death Valley]]'' (1941, Serial) \n* ''[[Hit the Road]]'' (1941) - Spike the Butcher\n* ''[[Hold That Ghost]]'' (1941) - High Collar (uncredited)\n* ''[[Treat 'Em Rough]]'' (1942) - Martin\n* ''[[True to the Army]]'' (1942) - Junior\n* ''[[Romance on the Range (film)|Romance on the Range]]'' (1942) - Jerome Banning\n* ''[[Flight Lieutenant (film)|Flight Lieutenant]]'' (1942) - Larsen (uncredited)\n* ''[[Eyes of the Underworld]]'' (1943) - Lance Merlin\n* ''[[The Desperadoes]]'' (1943) - Blackie (uncredited) (final film role)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0668023|name=Edward Pawley}}\n* {{IBDB name|55757}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pawley, Edward}}\n[[Category:1901 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male radio actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Kansas City, Missouri]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:People from Rappahannock County, Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Flowing Gold", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Pawley"}
{"title_page": "Florence Helena McGillivray", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Florence Helena McGillivray\n| image         = Florence H. McGillivray, 1937.png\n| imagesize     =\n| caption       = Florence H. McGillivray, 1937\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1864|3|1|mf=y}}\n| birth_place   = Township of [[Pickering, Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1938|5|7|1864|3|1|mf=y}} \n| death_place   = [[Toronto, Ontario]], Canada\n| nationality   = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| education     = Central Ontario School of Art, Academie de la Grande Chaumi\u00e8re\n| field         = [[Painting]]\n| training      =\n| movement      = \n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| awards        = \n| spouse        = \n}}\n\n'''Florence Helena McGillivray''' (1864&ndash;1938), was a Canadian landscape painter. Though McGillivray's main talent lay in landscape painting, she also practiced painting in watercolour during her career. Her paintings depicted many locations on the Gatineau River, the Val-des-Bois, the Ottawa River at Fort Coulonge and many more scenes of Canada and abroad.<ref name=\"cwahi.concordia.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://cwahi.concordia.ca/sources/artists/displayArtist.php?ID_artist=162|title=Canadian Women Artists History Initiative : Artist Database : Artists : MCGILLIVRAY, Florence Helena|website=cwahi.concordia.ca}}</ref>\n\nKnown for her Post Impressionistic style, McGillivray  in 1912, travelled to Paris to study. She was a well-known teacher.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://images.ourontario.ca/whitby/43070/data|title=Florence Helena McGillivray, 1906|last=Unknown|language=en|access-date=2017-03-09}}</ref> McGillivray's modernist art included textured, painterly brushstrokes applied with the palette knife and compelling colour. McGillivray was a contemporary of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]]. She encouraged the influential Canadian painter [[Tom Thomson]].\n\nIn the 1920s, McGillivray`s career exploded. Her art mainly was influenced by the Post-Impressionist and Fauvist movements. McGillivray lived in Whitby, Ottawa and Toronto but travelled often to pursue her work. She visited Europe, Alaska, Jamaica and Trinidad. Exhibition locations include Toronto Malloney's, Continental Galleries, Montreal, and her own studio in her hometown.\n\nThe National Gallery of Canada, the Art Gallery of Ontario, the Art Gallery of Hamilton, the Agnes Etherington Art Centre and galleries in Oshawa, Whitby, Kitchener, London, and Windsor all hold her work in their collections. McGillivray was an Associate member of the Royal Canadian Academy and a member of many associations such as the Ontario Society of Artists, the New York Society of Women Painters and Sculptors, and the Canadian Society of Painters in Water Colour as well as an Associate Member of the Royal Canadian Academy.<ref name=\":0\" /> Florence Helena McGillivray died in Toronto on May 7, 1938, and is buried at Union Cemetery, Oshawa.\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Florence H. Mc Gillivray.png|thumb|Florence Helena McGillivray, 1907]]\n\nFlorence Helena McGillivray was born in [[Pickering, Ontario|Pickering Township]] in Ontario on March 1, 1864 <ref> Allen, W C. (2019). She is one of the best : a researcher's notes on the life and times of canadian artist Florence... McGillivray. [S.l.]: Tellwell Talent. p. . ISBN 0-2288-0683-6. OCLC 1090427835</ref>. She was the eleventh of thirteen children, and the youngest female of the Scottish immigrant farmer, George McGillivray (1813-1894) and his wife, Caroline Amelia Fothergill McGillivray (1828-1909). \n\nIn 1870, the family moved to Inverlynn, a house located at 1300 Gifford Street in [[Whitby, Ontario]]. To this day, the property has remained in the possession of George McGillivray`s descendants. The children attended a grammar school in Whitby, and she had shown artistic talent in her early childhood years so she pursued her art by attending The Central Ontario School of Art, where she studied under Professor [[William Cruikshank (painter)|William Cruikshank]]. Florence then began taking one-on-one lessons from renowned Canadian artists such as [[Farquhar McGillivray Knowles]] and [[Lucius O\u2019Brien]] to name only a few.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gvhs.ca/publications/utga-following-florence.html|title=A Bridge A-Building|website=www.gvhs.ca|access-date=2017-03-09}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nAfter studying at the Ontario School of Art, McGillivray had private lessons with J.W.L. Forster, Lucius O'Brien and Farquhar McGillivray Knowles.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Independent Spirit: Early Canadian Women Artists|last=Parkash|first=A.K.|publisher=Firefly Books|year=2008|isbn=1554074177|location=New York|pages=355}}</ref> During the decade of 1900, she worked as a teacher in Whitby at the Ontario Ladies\u2019 College (now [[Trafalgar Castle School]]) and at Pickering College in Pickering, Ontario.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1913, she went to France to continue her studies at the [[Acad\u00e9mie de la Grande Chaumi\u00e8re|Academie de la Grande Chaumi\u00e8re]] under [[Lucien Simon]] and Menard.\n\n== Artistic career ==\n[[File:Afterglow, c. 1914.jpg|thumb|left|''Afterglow'', c. 1914, Florence H. McGillivray Canadian, 1864 - 1938 oil on paperboard 42 x 57.5&nbsp;cm. National Gallery of Canada (no. 1041)]]\n\nMcGillivray specialized as a landscape painter. She had a brilliant and unusual handling of brushwork that created unique compositions.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nShe was one of the first women artists to explore the landscape of northern Ontario and Quebec. She was part of the small group of artists that liked the romantic-realist view of the railway artists and the heroic view of the landscape in the 1890s that characterized the work of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]] and their adherents following the [[World War I|Great War]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=By a Lady: Celebrating Three Centuries of Art by Canadian Women|last=Tippett|first=Maria|publisher=Viking|year=1992|isbn=0140169555|location=Toronto|pages=|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/byladycelebratin0000tipp}}</ref>\n\nThroughout her life, she travelled across Canada, and to the United States, Jamaica, Trinidad, the Bahamas and Europe, as well as France, England and Italy, looking for new and challenging landscapes to paint.\n\n[[File:Contentment, c. 1914 Florence H. McGillivray.png|thumb|Contentment, c. 1913. Florence H. McGillivray Canadian, 1864 - 1938 oil on cardboard 41 x 32.7&nbsp;cm Art Gallery of Ontario]]\n[[File:Midwinter, Dunbarton, Ontario, 1918.jpg|thumb|Midwinter, Dunbarton, Ontario, 1918 Florence H. McGillivray Canadian, 1864 - 1938, Watercolour over graphite on illustration board 40.2 x 50.6&nbsp;cm, Purchased 1918 National Gallery of Canada (no. 1490)]]\n\nIn 1913, while in Paris, McGillvray had her painting ''Contentment'' (1913) exhibited at the Salon des Beaux Arts in Paris, the first great achievement on her career. In the same year, she was also said to have been elected president of the International Art Union.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nMcGillivray moved back to Canada in 1914. The most prolific and vibrant phase of her artistic career occurred during the 1920s while she lived in Ottawa, where she set up a studio at Frank Street. [[:File:///H:/Documents/Downloads/CORRECTIONS.docx# edn4|[iv]]] Her work from this period is rich in colour and texture, reflecting the Post-Impressionist work she had encountered in Europe. [[:File:///H:/Documents/Downloads/CORRECTIONS.docx# edn5|[v]]]\n\nShe had a method of rendering forms in massed areas of colour applied in places with the palette knife and strong black lines around forms, a style seldom seen in Canada before her work.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Tom Thomson: Design for a Canadian Hero|last=Murray|first=Joan|publisher=Dundurn Press|year=1998|isbn=1550023152|location=Toronto|pages=76\u201377}}</ref> This technique was also used by [[Tom Thomson]], who admired her and said of her, \"she is one of the best\".<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThree of her paintings are part of the [[National Gallery of Canada]] collection, ''Midwinter, Dunbarton, Ontario'' (1918), ''Afterglow'' (1914), and ''St. Anthony Harbour, Newfoundland'', (1926).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gallery.ca/en/see/collections/artwork.php?mkey=11027.|title=Midwinter, Dunbarton, Ontario. Florence H. McGillivray 1918|website=www.gallery.ca|language=en-ca|access-date=2017-03-09}}</ref>\n\n=== Exhibition ===\n*1913 Paris Salon des Beaux Arts, exhibited Contentment\n*1914 - 1935 exhibited with the Royal Canadian Academy of Arts\n*1917 - 1938 exhibited with the Ontario Society of Artists\n*1920 - 1930 exhibition venues included Malloney's in Toronto, Continental Galleries in Montreal; and artist's own Frank Street Studio in Ottawa\n*1924 British Empire Exhibition, Canadian Section of Fine Arts, Wembley, England\n*1927 Exposition d\u2019art canadien, Musee du Jeu de Paume, Paris\n*1928 Exhibition of Paintings of At Home and Abroad by F.H. McGillivray, A.R.C.A., O.S.A., Art Association of Montreal\n*1970 retrospective exhibition, Whitby Arts, Whitby, Ontario\n*2002 The Birth of the Modern: Post-Impressionism in Canadian Art, c.1900-1920, Robert McLaughlin Gallery, Oshawa; travelled to Montreal, London (Ontario), Fredericton, and Winnipeg\n*2017 Finding Florence, retrospective exhibition, Station Gallery, Whitby, Ontario <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stationgallery.ca/exhibitions/finding-florence/|title=Finding Florence|website=www.stationgallery.ca}}</ref>\n\n== Affiliation ==\nFlorence Helena McGillivray was affiliated with a multiple of associations, groups and artists during her lifetime. One of the most famous groups that she was associated with was the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]]. Her art works expresses a view of landscape in bold colours that would be categorized later on as part of the Group of Seven landscape painting that captures the two visions of the land: the romantic-realist view of the railway artists of the 1880s and the heroic view of the landscape in the 1890s.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nShe joined the Womens Art Association of Canada where she studied painting on china with Mary E. Dignam, its founding president.<ref name=\":1\" /> McGillivray was welcomed into communities and numerous social affairs which included the Society of Women Painters and Sculptors and the Women Painters and Sculptors Art Club (Women Painters and Sculptors 1917) which were both centralized in New York City.<ref name=\"cwahi.concordia.ca\" /> She continued her study of painting on china  with Marshall Fry in New York in 1898 and sold her pieces later from her studio in Whitby <ref name=\":1\" />. She also gave painting classes in Whitby.<ref name=\":1\" /> She became an instructor and a critic at an all boys\u2019 school in Pickering College and an assistant art instructor at the Ontario's Ladies\u2019 College in the 1900s and later, the head of the art department.<ref name=\"images.ourontario.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://images.ourontario.ca/whitby/43070/data|title=Florence Helena McGillivray, 1906|website=images.ourontario.ca}}</ref> \n\nThe artist also helped encourage fellow Canadian artist [[Tom Thomson]], who was praised for his landscape paintings.<ref name=\":2\" /> In 1913 during her trip in Paris, her instructors  at the [[Acad\u00e9mie de la Grande Chaumi\u00e8re|Academie de la Grande Chaumi\u00e8re]] were Lucien Simon and Emile-Rene Menard. But her real inspiration was the artist Frederic Fiebig<ref>{{Cite book|last=Allen |first=W C.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1090427835|title=She is one of the best : a researcher's notes on the life and times of canadian artist Florence... McGillivray.|date=2019|publisher=Tellwell Talent|year=|isbn=0-2288-0683-6|location=[S.l.]|pages=74-75|oclc=1090427835}}</ref> and due to him, she began to work in a style new to her that involved using the palette knife and a heavier application of paint. Her works of art in this mode were acknowledged and she was invited to display her paintings at the Salon des Beaux Arts.<ref name=\"cwahi.concordia.ca\" /> Not long later, it is said, the artist was voted as president of the International Union.<ref name=\":2\" />  In the later years of McGillivray's life she joined the [[Ontario Society of Artists]] (1917), she was elected an Associate member of the [[Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]](1924),<ref name=\":1\" /> and was a Charter member of the Canadian Society of Painters in Watercolour and its first woman member (1925). <ref name=\"images.ourontario.ca\" />\n\n== Influence and Style ==\n[[File:St. Anthony Harbour, Newfoundland, Florence H. McGillivray.jpg|thumb|St. Anthony Harbour, Newfoundland, Florence H. McGillivray Canadian, 1864 - 1938 oil on canvas 46.7 x 61.6&nbsp;cm Purchased 1926 National Gallery of Canada (no. 3352)]]\n\nMcGillivray traveled across Canada for inspiration.<ref name=\":1\" /> She painted her environment using bold colours and the contour of shapes.<ref name=\":1\" /> McGillivray's artistic style stressed the \"abstract qualities of lines, shapes and forms\"<ref name=\":1\" /> that was expressed in her work through a large amount of paint applied using the palette knife in her oil paintings.<ref name=\":1\" /> Working outdoors, the painter developed a powerful style that defined her career.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nHer inspiration derived from various environments<ref name=\":1\" /> including her hometown of Whitby, and her travel to the Gatineau area <ref name=\":0\" />, as well as to Eastern Canada, including Newfoundland, and to Trinidad, Jamaica, Bahama Islands in the West Indies, Alaska, Eastern United States, Western Canada, Venice, Italy and the Swiss Alps.<ref name=\"cwahi.concordia.ca\" /> She worked in many media which included watercolour, pastel and oil.<ref name=\":1\" /> During her trip to Europe, she had encountered newly forming art styles of Symbolism and Post Impressionism that impacted and influenced her art. Her artwork is expressed mainly with vivid colours of contouring shapes and dabs of paint that simplifies the form of an object.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Later Years==\nMcGillivray traveled extensively in search of new landscape scenery to paint. In 1930, by then in her mid-60s, McGillivray bought a house in Toronto where she retired.<ref name=\":1\" /> She continued to paint primarily from the sketches she had accumulated from around the world. As a landscape painter, McGillivray found some prestige and recognition while alive, but not quite as much as Thomson though she had encouraged him in his modernist path. Painting landscapes in a modernist style was not something expected from a woman in the early 1900s. McGillivray never married and left no children. She died at age 74 in Toronto, on May 7, 1938.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* Allen, Bill. \"Up the Gatineau!\" ''Following Florence'' XLII, 2016.\n* Allen, W C. She is one of the best : a researcher's notes on the life and times of Canadian Artist Florence... McGillivray. Tellwell Talent, 2019. {{ISBN |0-2288-0683-6|}}\n* Art Gallery of Ontario. \"The Canadian Collection.\" ''Art Gallery of Ontario'', 288-289. New York: McGraw-Hill Company of Canada, 1970.\n* Canadian Women Artists History Initiative. 2016. <ref></ref>''[http://cwahi.concordia.ca/sources/artists/displayArtist.php?ID_artist=162 Artist Database]'' August 15. Accessed January 2017.\n* Haggo, Regina, \"[http://www.thespec.com/whatson-story/7050268-regina-haggo-florence-mcgillivray-tamed-nature-with-a-brush/ Florence McGillivray Tamed Nature with a Brush]\" The Spectator (2017) Accessed January, 2017. \n* Murray, Joan. Tom Thomson'': Design For a Canadian Hero''. Toronto, Ont.: Dundurn Press, 1998. 76-77. Canadian Electronic Library/desLibris. Web. 23 Jan. 2017.\n* Prakash, A. K. ''Independent Spirit'', 355 & 399. New York: Firefly Books, 2008.\n* Royal Canadian Academy Annual Exhibition: (Montreal, November 18, 1937) \"Royal Canadian Academy Show is Opened at Art Association. Portraiture Represented by Good Examples and Landscapes as Usual Predominate.\"  Gazette (Montreal)  November 19, 1937.  P.12.\n* Ten-Doesschate Chu, Petra and Touborg, Sarah. Nineteenth Century European Art. Upper Saddle, NJ: Pearson Education, 2006.\n* Tippett, Maria. By a lady'': Celebrating Three Centuries of Art by Canadian Women''. Toronto: Viking, 1992.\n* Whitby Archives. 2016. ''[http://vitacollections.ca/whitbynews/68663/data?n=1 Archives at Whitby Public Library]''.\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Agnes Etherington Art Centre (2008), Permanent collection, 1968, University of Michigan\n* Art Gallery of Ontario (1970), Art Gallery of Ontario: A Canadian Collection, McGraw-Hill Company of Canada, {{ISBN|9780070925045}}\n*W.C Allen (2016), ''A Collection of Works by Florence Helena McGillivray,'' Friesen Press, {{ISBN|9781460285718}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McGillivray, Florence Helena}}\n[[Category:1864 births]]\n[[Category:1938 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]]\n[[Category:Canadian women painters]]\n[[Category:19th-century Canadian painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian painters]]\n[[Category:19th-century women artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian women artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Florence Helena McGillivray\n| image         = Florence H. McGillivray, 1937.png\n| imagesize     =\n| caption       = Florence H. McGillivray, 1937\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1864|3|1|mf=y}}\n| birth_place   = Township of [[Pickering, Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1938|5|7|1864|3|1|mf=y}} \n| death_place   = [[Toronto, Ontario]], Canada\n| nationality   = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| education     = Central Ontario School of Art, Academie de la Grande Chaumi\u00e8re\n| field         = [[Painting]]\n| training      =\n| movement      = \n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| awards        = \n| spouse        = \n}}\n\n'''Florence Helena McGillivray''' (1864&ndash;1938), was a Canadian landscape painter. Though McGillivray's main talent lay in landscape painting, she also practiced painting in watercolour during her career. Her paintings depicted many locations on the Gatineau River, the Val-des-Bois, the Ottawa River at Fort Coulonge and many more scenes of Canada and abroad.<ref name=\"cwahi.concordia.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://cwahi.concordia.ca/sources/artists/displayArtist.php?ID_artist=162|title=Canadian Women Artists History Initiative : Artist Database : Artists : MCGILLIVRAY, Florence Helena|website=cwahi.concordia.ca}}</ref>\n\nKnown for her Post Impressionistic style, McGillivray  in 1912, travelled to Paris to study. She was a well-known teacher.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://images.ourontario.ca/whitby/43070/data|title=Florence Helena McGillivray, 1906|last=Unknown|language=en|access-date=2017-03-09}}</ref> McGillivray's modernist art included textured, painterly brushstrokes applied with the palette knife and compelling colour. McGillivray was a contemporary of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]]. She encouraged the influential Canadian painter [[Tom Thomson]].\n\nIn the 1920s, McGillivray`s career exploded. Her art mainly was influenced by the Post-Impressionist and Fauvist movements. McGillivray lived in Whitby, Ottawa and Toronto but travelled often to pursue her work. She visited Europe, Alaska, Jamaica and Trinidad. Exhibition locations include Toronto Malloney's, Continental Galleries, Montreal, and her own studio in her hometown.\n\nThe National Gallery of Canada, the Art Gallery of Ontario, the Art Gallery of Hamilton, the Agnes Etherington Art Centre and galleries in Oshawa, Whitby, Kitchener, London, and Windsor all hold her work in their collections. McGillivray was an Associate member of the Royal Canadian Academy and a member of many associations such as the Ontario Society of Artists, the New York Society of Women Painters and Sculptors, and the Canadian Society of Painters in Water Colour as well as an Associate Member of the Royal Canadian Academy.<ref name=\":0\" /> Florence Helena McGillivray died in Toronto on May 7, 1938, and is buried at Union Cemetery, Oshawa.\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Florence H. Mc Gillivray.png|thumb|Florence Helena McGillivray, 1907]]\n\nFlorence Helena McGillivray was born in [[Pickering, Ontario|Pickering Township]] in Ontario on March 1, 1864 <ref>ref name=>{{Cite book|title=She is one of the best : a researcher's notes on the life and times of Canadian Artist Florence... McGillivray|last=Allen|first=W.C.|publisher= Tellwell Talent|year=2019|isbn= 0-2288-0683-6||Page=  .</ref>. She was the eleventh of thirteen children, and the youngest female of the Scottish immigrant farmer, George McGillivray (1813-1894) and his wife, Caroline Amelia Fothergill McGillivray (1828-1909). \n\nIn 1870, the family moved to Inverlynn, a house located at 1300 Gifford Street in [[Whitby, Ontario]]. To this day, the property has remained in the possession of George McGillivray`s descendants. The children attended a grammar school in Whitby, and she had shown artistic talent in her early childhood years so she pursued her art by attending The Central Ontario School of Art, where she studied under Professor [[William Cruikshank (painter)|William Cruikshank]]. Florence then began taking one-on-one lessons from renowned Canadian artists such as [[Farquhar McGillivray Knowles]] and [[Lucius O\u2019Brien]] to name only a few.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gvhs.ca/publications/utga-following-florence.html|title=A Bridge A-Building|website=www.gvhs.ca|access-date=2017-03-09}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nAfter studying at the Ontario School of Art, McGillivray had private lessons with J.W.L. Forster, Lucius O'Brien and Farquhar McGillivray Knowles.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Independent Spirit: Early Canadian Women Artists|last=Parkash|first=A.K.|publisher=Firefly Books|year=2008|isbn=1554074177|location=New York|pages=355}}</ref> During the decade of 1900, she worked as a teacher in Whitby at the Ontario Ladies\u2019 College (now [[Trafalgar Castle School]]) and at Pickering College in Pickering, Ontario.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1913, she went to France to continue her studies at the [[Acad\u00e9mie de la Grande Chaumi\u00e8re|Academie de la Grande Chaumi\u00e8re]] under [[Lucien Simon]] and Menard.\n\n== Artistic career ==\n[[File:Afterglow, c. 1914.jpg|thumb|left|''Afterglow'', c. 1914, Florence H. McGillivray Canadian, 1864 - 1938 oil on paperboard 42 x 57.5&nbsp;cm. National Gallery of Canada (no. 1041)]]\n\nMcGillivray specialized as a landscape painter. She had a brilliant and unusual handling of brushwork that created unique compositions.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nShe was one of the first women artists to explore the landscape of northern Ontario and Quebec. She was part of the small group of artists that liked the romantic-realist view of the railway artists and the heroic view of the landscape in the 1890s that characterized the work of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]] and their adherents following the [[World War I|Great War]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=By a Lady: Celebrating Three Centuries of Art by Canadian Women|last=Tippett|first=Maria|publisher=Viking|year=1992|isbn=0140169555|location=Toronto|pages=|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/byladycelebratin0000tipp}}</ref>\n\nThroughout her life, she travelled across Canada, and to the United States, Jamaica, Trinidad, the Bahamas and Europe, as well as France, England and Italy, looking for new and challenging landscapes to paint.\n\n[[File:Contentment, c. 1914 Florence H. McGillivray.png|thumb|Contentment, c. 1913. Florence H. McGillivray Canadian, 1864 - 1938 oil on cardboard 41 x 32.7&nbsp;cm Art Gallery of Ontario]]\n[[File:Midwinter, Dunbarton, Ontario, 1918.jpg|thumb|Midwinter, Dunbarton, Ontario, 1918 Florence H. McGillivray Canadian, 1864 - 1938, Watercolour over graphite on illustration board 40.2 x 50.6&nbsp;cm, Purchased 1918 National Gallery of Canada (no. 1490)]]\n\nIn 1913, while in Paris, McGillvray had her painting ''Contentment'' (1913) exhibited at the Salon des Beaux Arts in Paris, the first great achievement on her career. In the same year, she was also said to have been elected president of the International Art Union.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nMcGillivray moved back to Canada in 1914. The most prolific and vibrant phase of her artistic career occurred during the 1920s while she lived in Ottawa, where she set up a studio at Frank Street. [[:File:///H:/Documents/Downloads/CORRECTIONS.docx# edn4|[iv]]] Her work from this period is rich in colour and texture, reflecting the Post-Impressionist work she had encountered in Europe. [[:File:///H:/Documents/Downloads/CORRECTIONS.docx# edn5|[v]]]\n\nShe had a method of rendering forms in massed areas of colour applied in places with the palette knife and strong black lines around forms, a style seldom seen in Canada before her work.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Tom Thomson: Design for a Canadian Hero|last=Murray|first=Joan|publisher=Dundurn Press|year=1998|isbn=1550023152|location=Toronto|pages=76\u201377}}</ref> This technique was also used by [[Tom Thomson]], who admired her and said of her, \"she is one of the best\".<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThree of her paintings are part of the [[National Gallery of Canada]] collection, ''Midwinter, Dunbarton, Ontario'' (1918), ''Afterglow'' (1914), and ''St. Anthony Harbour, Newfoundland'', (1926).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gallery.ca/en/see/collections/artwork.php?mkey=11027.|title=Midwinter, Dunbarton, Ontario. Florence H. McGillivray 1918|website=www.gallery.ca|language=en-ca|access-date=2017-03-09}}</ref>\n\n=== Exhibition ===\n*1913 Paris Salon des Beaux Arts, exhibited Contentment\n*1914 - 1935 exhibited with the Royal Canadian Academy of Arts\n*1917 - 1938 exhibited with the Ontario Society of Artists\n*1920 - 1930 exhibition venues included Malloney's in Toronto, Continental Galleries in Montreal; and artist's own Frank Street Studio in Ottawa\n*1924 British Empire Exhibition, Canadian Section of Fine Arts, Wembley, England\n*1927 Exposition d\u2019art canadien, Musee du Jeu de Paume, Paris\n*1928 Exhibition of Paintings of At Home and Abroad by F.H. McGillivray, A.R.C.A., O.S.A., Art Association of Montreal\n*1970 retrospective exhibition, Whitby Arts, Whitby, Ontario\n*2002 The Birth of the Modern: Post-Impressionism in Canadian Art, c.1900-1920, Robert McLaughlin Gallery, Oshawa; travelled to Montreal, London (Ontario), Fredericton, and Winnipeg\n*2017 Finding Florence, retrospective exhibition, Station Gallery, Whitby, Ontario <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stationgallery.ca/exhibitions/finding-florence/|title=Finding Florence|website=www.stationgallery.ca}}</ref>\n\n== Affiliation ==\nFlorence Helena McGillivray was affiliated with a multiple of associations, groups and artists during her lifetime. One of the most famous groups that she was associated with was the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]]. Her art works expresses a view of landscape in bold colours that would be categorized later on as part of the Group of Seven landscape painting that captures the two visions of the land: the romantic-realist view of the railway artists of the 1880s and the heroic view of the landscape in the 1890s.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nShe joined the Womens Art Association of Canada where she studied painting on china with Mary E. Dignam, its founding president.<ref name=\":1\" /> McGillivray was welcomed into communities and numerous social affairs which included the Society of Women Painters and Sculptors and the Women Painters and Sculptors Art Club (Women Painters and Sculptors 1917) which were both centralized in New York City.<ref name=\"cwahi.concordia.ca\" /> She continued her study of painting on china  with Marshall Fry in New York in 1898 and sold her pieces later from her studio in Whitby <ref name=\":1\" />. She also gave painting classes in Whitby.<ref name=\":1\" /> She became an instructor and a critic at an all boys\u2019 school in Pickering College and an assistant art instructor at the Ontario's Ladies\u2019 College in the 1900s and later, the head of the art department.<ref name=\"images.ourontario.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://images.ourontario.ca/whitby/43070/data|title=Florence Helena McGillivray, 1906|website=images.ourontario.ca}}</ref> \n\nThe artist also helped encourage fellow Canadian artist [[Tom Thomson]], who was praised for his landscape paintings.<ref name=\":2\" /> In 1913 during her trip in Paris, her instructors  at the [[Acad\u00e9mie de la Grande Chaumi\u00e8re|Academie de la Grande Chaumi\u00e8re]] were Lucien Simon and Emile-Rene Menard. But her real inspiration was the artist Frederic Fiebig<ref>{{Cite book|last=Allen |first=W C.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1090427835|title=She is one of the best : a researcher's notes on the life and times of canadian artist Florence... McGillivray.|date=2019|publisher=Tellwell Talent|year=|isbn=0-2288-0683-6|location=[S.l.]|pages=74-75|oclc=1090427835}}</ref> and due to him, she began to work in a style new to her that involved using the palette knife and a heavier application of paint. Her works of art in this mode were acknowledged and she was invited to display her paintings at the Salon des Beaux Arts.<ref name=\"cwahi.concordia.ca\" /> Not long later, it is said, the artist was voted as president of the International Union.<ref name=\":2\" />  In the later years of McGillivray's life she joined the [[Ontario Society of Artists]] (1917), she was elected an Associate member of the [[Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]](1924),<ref name=\":1\" /> and was a Charter member of the Canadian Society of Painters in Watercolour and its first woman member (1925). <ref name=\"images.ourontario.ca\" />\n\n== Influence and Style ==\n[[File:St. Anthony Harbour, Newfoundland, Florence H. McGillivray.jpg|thumb|St. Anthony Harbour, Newfoundland, Florence H. McGillivray Canadian, 1864 - 1938 oil on canvas 46.7 x 61.6&nbsp;cm Purchased 1926 National Gallery of Canada (no. 3352)]]\n\nMcGillivray traveled across Canada for inspiration.<ref name=\":1\" /> She painted her environment using bold colours and the contour of shapes.<ref name=\":1\" /> McGillivray's artistic style stressed the \"abstract qualities of lines, shapes and forms\"<ref name=\":1\" /> that was expressed in her work through a large amount of paint applied using the palette knife in her oil paintings.<ref name=\":1\" /> Working outdoors, the painter developed a powerful style that defined her career.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nHer inspiration derived from various environments<ref name=\":1\" /> including her hometown of Whitby, and her travel to the Gatineau area <ref name=\":0\" />, as well as to Eastern Canada, including Newfoundland, and to Trinidad, Jamaica, Bahama Islands in the West Indies, Alaska, Eastern United States, Western Canada, Venice, Italy and the Swiss Alps.<ref name=\"cwahi.concordia.ca\" /> She worked in many media which included watercolour, pastel and oil.<ref name=\":1\" /> During her trip to Europe, she had encountered newly forming art styles of Symbolism and Post Impressionism that impacted and influenced her art. Her artwork is expressed mainly with vivid colours of contouring shapes and dabs of paint that simplifies the form of an object.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Later Years==\nMcGillivray traveled extensively in search of new landscape scenery to paint. In 1930, by then in her mid-60s, McGillivray bought a house in Toronto where she retired.<ref name=\":1\" /> She continued to paint primarily from the sketches she had accumulated from around the world. As a landscape painter, McGillivray found some prestige and recognition while alive, but not quite as much as Thomson though she had encouraged him in his modernist path. Painting landscapes in a modernist style was not something expected from a woman in the early 1900s. McGillivray never married and left no children. She died at age 74 in Toronto, on May 7, 1938.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* Allen, Bill. \"Up the Gatineau!\" ''Following Florence'' XLII, 2016.\n* Allen, W C. She is one of the best : a researcher's notes on the life and times of Canadian Artist Florence... McGillivray. Tellwell Talent, 2019. {{ISBN |0-2288-0683-6|}}\n* Art Gallery of Ontario. \"The Canadian Collection.\" ''Art Gallery of Ontario'', 288-289. New York: McGraw-Hill Company of Canada, 1970.\n* Canadian Women Artists History Initiative. 2016. <ref></ref>''[http://cwahi.concordia.ca/sources/artists/displayArtist.php?ID_artist=162 Artist Database]'' August 15. Accessed January 2017.\n* Haggo, Regina, \"[http://www.thespec.com/whatson-story/7050268-regina-haggo-florence-mcgillivray-tamed-nature-with-a-brush/ Florence McGillivray Tamed Nature with a Brush]\" The Spectator (2017) Accessed January, 2017. \n* Murray, Joan. Tom Thomson'': Design For a Canadian Hero''. Toronto, Ont.: Dundurn Press, 1998. 76-77. Canadian Electronic Library/desLibris. Web. 23 Jan. 2017.\n* Prakash, A. K. ''Independent Spirit'', 355 & 399. New York: Firefly Books, 2008.\n* Royal Canadian Academy Annual Exhibition: (Montreal, November 18, 1937) \"Royal Canadian Academy Show is Opened at Art Association. Portraiture Represented by Good Examples and Landscapes as Usual Predominate.\"  Gazette (Montreal)  November 19, 1937.  P.12.\n* Ten-Doesschate Chu, Petra and Touborg, Sarah. Nineteenth Century European Art. Upper Saddle, NJ: Pearson Education, 2006.\n* Tippett, Maria. By a lady'': Celebrating Three Centuries of Art by Canadian Women''. Toronto: Viking, 1992.\n* Whitby Archives.